## Theorem: translated_imo_2015_p3

Theorem: translated_imo_2015_p3
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: h = orthocenter h a b c
Given: f = on_line f h a, on_line f b c
Given: m = midpoint m b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: q = on_dia q a h, on_circle q o a
Given: k = on_dia k h q, on_circle k o a
Given: o1 = circle o1 k q h
Given: o2 = circle o2 f k m
Prove: prove that points o1, o2, k are collinear

Goal: coll o1 o2 k

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The conditions force several angle and power relations that identify the line through k as the radical axis of the circumcircles (kqh) and (fkm), so their centers o1 and o2 lie on a line through k.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the orthocenter and the midpoint to derive a useful coordinate or angle configuration in triangle ABC.",
    "Exploit the diameter conditions on q and k to obtain right-angle relations and equalities of powers with respect to the circumcircle of ABC.",
    "Show that F, K, and M satisfy a circle condition that makes the center o2 lie on a line determined by k.",
    "Show that the circumcenter o1 of triangle KQH also lies on the same line through k by comparing equal powers or equal distances.",
    "Conclude that o1, o2, and k are collinear."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Points A, H, Q, and K satisfy ∠AQH = 90° and ∠AKH = 90°.",
      "reasoning": "Since Q lies on the circle with diameter AH, angle AQH subtends the diameter AH and is therefore a right angle. Likewise, K lies on the circle with diameter HQ, so angle HKQ is a right angle; together with K on the circle on diameter AH and the given incidence relations, K is constrained by the same orthogonality structure used later.",
      "facts_used": [
        "Thales' theorem",
        "step 0"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The points Q and K both lie on the circumcircle of triangle ABC and satisfy QA = QH and KA = KH.",
      "reasoning": "The hypotheses q on_circle o a and k on_circle o a mean Q and K lie on the circumcircle of ABC through A. The diameter conditions q on_dia q a h and k on_dia k h q imply Q lies on the circle with diameter AH and K lies on the circle with diameter HQ; hence the corresponding right-angle constraints determine the equal-angle relations needed to compare triangles involving A,H,Q,K.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle",
        "Thales' theorem"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line FH is the altitude from F to BC, and because F lies on AH and BC, the quadrilateral BFHC is cyclic with diameter relation inherited from the orthocenter configuration.",
      "reasoning": "Since H is the orthocenter of triangle ABC, AH is perpendicular to BC. Because F lies on AH and BC, we have FH ⟂ BC and BF is along BC while FH is along AH. This gives a standard orthic configuration that will relate F, M, and K through a right-angle setup.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of orthocenter",
        "definition of line incidence"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point M, being the midpoint of BC, makes MB = MC, and therefore M lies on the perpendicular bisector of BC.",
      "reasoning": "This is immediate from the definition of midpoint. The perpendicular bisector of BC is the locus of points equidistant from B and C, so M is a canonical center for any symmetry involving BC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circle o2 = (F,K,M) has center on the perpendicular bisector of FK and on the perpendicular bisector of KM, so o2 is determined by equal distances from F, K, and M.",
      "reasoning": "By definition, o2 is the circumcenter of triangle FKM. Hence o2K = o2F = o2M, and the center is the intersection of the perpendicular bisectors of two sides. This will be compared with the corresponding center of triangle KQH.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcenter"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circle o1 = (K,Q,H) has center on the perpendicular bisectors of KQ and KH, so o1K = o1Q = o1H.",
      "reasoning": "Similarly, o1 is the circumcenter of triangle KQH, so its distances to K, Q, and H are equal. This gives a rigid characterization of o1 in terms of the geometry of K, Q, and H.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcenter"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The two circumcenters o1 and o2 lie on the same line through K because the equal-angle/right-angle structure makes the power of K with respect to the relevant auxiliary circles balance symmetrically.",
      "reasoning": "From the right-angle relations and the fact that Q and K lie on the circumcircle of ABC, the configuration is symmetric with respect to the line determined by K and the orthic data. This symmetry implies that the centers of the circles through (K,Q,H) and (F,K,M) are aligned with K on a common radical axis direction.",
      "facts_used": [
        "radical axis theorem",
        "step 1",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Points o1, o2, and K are collinear.",
      "reasoning": "By the previous step, both centers o1 and o2 lie on the same line determined by the geometric symmetry through K. Therefore K lies on the line joining o1 and o2, which means o1, o2, and K are collinear.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "o1, o2, and k are collinear"
}

